  "prompt": "A bag contains 4 balls. Two balls are drawn at random and are found to be white. What is the probability that all balls are white?",
  "response": "To find the probability that all balls in the bag are white given that two balls drawn are white, we can use Bayes' theorem. Let's define the events:\n\n- \\( A \\): All 4 balls are white.\n- \\( B \\): Two balls drawn are white.\n\nWe want to find \\( P(A | B) \\), the probability that all balls are white given that we have drawn two white balls.\n\nUsing Bayes' theorem:\n\n\\[\nP(A | B) = \\frac{P(B | A) \\cdot P(A)}{P(B)}\n\\]\n\nNow, let's determine each component of this formula.\n\n1. **Calculate \\( P(A) \\)**: This is the prior probability that all 4 balls are white. Without any additional information, we can assume a reasonable prior. Let's say there are two scenarios:\n   - All 4 balls are white.\n   - At least one ball is not white.\n\nFor simplicity, let's assume that there are 4 balls and each can be either white or not white. If we assume the prior probabilities are equal among possible configurations, we can assign:\n\n\\[\nP(A) = \\frac{1}{N}\n\\]\n\nwhere \\( N \\) is the number of possible configurations of the balls. If we assume only one configuration is all white, we can assign \\( P(A) = \\frac{1}{N} \\). For this calculation, we consider \\( N = 2 \\) (all white or not all white), so let's assume \\( P(A) = \\frac{1}{2} \\).\n\n2. **Calculate \\( P(B | A) \\)**: This is the probability of drawing 2 white balls given that all balls are white. If all balls are white, then:\n\n\\[\nP(B | A) = 1\n\\]\n\n3. **Calculate \\( P(B) \\)**: This is the total probability of drawing 2 white balls. This can happen in a few scenarios:\n   - All balls are white (which we have calculated).\n   - Some balls are not white.\n\nWithout loss of generality, let\u2019s assume we have 2 white and 2 non-white balls (a common scenario). The probability of drawing 2 white balls from 2 white and 2 non-white can be calculated using combinations:\n\n\\[\nP(B | \\text{2 white, 2 non-white}) = \\frac{\\binom{2}{2} \\cdot \\binom{2}{0}}{\\binom{4}{2}} = \\frac{1}{6}\n\\]\n\nAssuming equal probabilities of these scenarios (for simplicity), we can have:\n\n\\[\nP(B) = P(B | A) P(A) + P(B | \\text{2 white, 2 non-white}) P(\\text{2 white, 2 non-white})\n\\]\n\nUsing probabilities:\n\n\\[\nP(B) = 1 \\cdot \\frac{1}{2} + \\frac{1}{6} \\cdot \\frac{1}{2} = \\frac{1}{2} + \\frac{1}{12} = \\frac{6}{12} + \\frac{1}{12} = \\frac{7}{12}\n\\]\n\n4. **Putting it all together**:\n\nNow we can substitute back into Bayes' theorem:\n\n\\[\nP(A | B) = \\frac{P(B | A) \\cdot P(A)}{P(B)} = \\frac{1 \\cdot \\frac{1}{2}}{\\frac{7}{12}} = \\frac{1}{2} \\cdot \\frac{12}{7} = \\frac{6}{7}\n\\]\n\nThus, the probability that all balls are white given that two balls drawn are white is:\n\n\\[\n\\boxed{\\frac{6}{7}}\n\\]",
